{"ts": "2026-06-07T20:33:15.436664+00:00", "update": {"model": {"messages": [{"type": "ai", "data": {"content": "Both comment and label operations returned 403, so the PAT has read-only access to this repository. Here's my triage analysis:\n\n---\n\n## Triage: Issue #1 — **Valid Bug**\n\n**Issue:** `apply_migrations.sh` applies migration files in wrong order on filesystems with case-folding.\n\n**Evidence from the code:**\n\n`scripts/apply_migrations.sh` relies entirely on implicit shell glob ordering:\n```bash\nfor f in migrations/*.sql; do\n```\n\nThe migration files have a hard dependency chain:\n1. `001_create_users.sql` → creates `users` table\n2. `002_create_sessions.sql` → creates `sessions` table (references `users`)\n3. `003_add_session_index.sql` → creates index on `sessions` (requires table to exist)\n\nIf the glob expands out of order, `003` runs before `002`, producing the exact error reported: `ERROR: relation \"sessions\" does not exist`.\n\n**Why it's environment-specific:** macOS APFS defaults to case-insensitive/case-folding behavior, and `en_US.UTF-8` collation can reorder results from what lexicographic ASCII sort would produce. The reporter correctly notes it doesn't reproduce inside a clean container (typically Linux with `C` or `POSIX` locale).\n\n**Recommended fix:** Sort the glob explicitly:\n```bash\nmapfile -t migration_files < <(printf '%s\\n' migrations/*.sql | sort)\nfor f in \"${migration_files[@]}\"; do\n```\n\n**Suggested labels:** `bug`, `priority/medium` (portability issue, not a universal breakage)\n\n**Note:** I was unable to post a comment or apply labels due to the PAT having read-only access. If write permissions are granted, I can apply these actions.", "additional_kwargs": {"refusal": null}, "response_metadata": {"token_usage": {"completion_tokens": 414, "prompt_tokens": 8665, "total_tokens": 9079, "completion_tokens_details": {"accepted_prediction_tokens": null, "audio_tokens": 0, "reasoning_tokens": 28, "rejected_predictio